@eric-wieser Weird, when committing your suggestion it doesn't seem to have picked up the underscore characters which I believe is what is causing the build errors now.  Looks like a github bug.

Can you also show the similar (and perhaps easier to prove)
```lean
    (Subgroup.normalClosure s).comap f = Subgroup.normalClosure (f ⁻¹' s) := by
```
Good idea. I think `Subgroup.normalClosure (f ⁻¹' s) ≤ (Subgroup.normalClosure s).comap f` holds for any homomorphism `f : G →* N`.
In my opinion this should be the umprime version, and we can even drop the other one (I didn't check all the version, but it is coherent with the version for ring equiv).
Yeah, I agree with that based off of what you said (I haven't researched whether this is the general convention) but curious if others agree?  @eric-wieser @alreadydone ?
Will this mess up the #align for mathport (I am completely ignorant of this and whether we can change the names that are currently there -- this would be needed afaict) ?

You should adjust the `#align` to point to the best match for the mathlib3 statement, if one exists. So here, either change the align to point to the primed name (if you keep both), or just leave it alone (if you change the existing statement as Riccardo suggests)

```suggestion
    (normalClosure s).comap f = normalClosure (f ⁻¹' s) := by
```

I think this would make more sense as
```suggestion
theorem Subgroup.map_normalClosure {s : Set G} (f : G ≃* N) :
    (normalClosure s).map f = normalClosure (f '' s) := by
```
as this matches `map_closure`

```suggestion simp only [coe_comap, ← Set.image_subset_iff] ```
I pushed a golf here: the result is that this lemma should only need `f` to be surjective, not an equivalence. Can you update things accordingly?
I think I originally misunderstood what you meant here and pushed still using `f` as an equivalence.  Will take another stab at it.
What you pushed is what *I* originally meant, but @alreadydone suggested it might be true more generally
I think my comment above still applies; instead of using `f.surjective`, can you add `hf : Surjective f`, and replace `f` with a `MonoidHom`?
Yes, latest update now uses a `MonoidHom` and its surjection explicitly now.
Is the `@` really needed here?

> Is the `@` really needed here?

Nope, removed.

```suggestion
theorem Subgroup.map_normalClosure (s : Set G) (f : G →* N) (hf : Surjective f) :
```
and below
Personally I don't see much point in keeping these `toMonoidHom` versions around now, but your call.

@tb65536 Yeah, @riccardobrasca had a similar sentiment.  I don't have any particularly strong opinions as I am still somewhat new to Mathlib and still learning my way around and open to whatever the reviewers think is best.  @eric-wieser any opinions on this?

Maybe this is best saved for another PR, but you can weaken this to `Surjective f` under the assumption that `s` is `Nonempty`:
```lean
theorem Subgroup.ker_le_closure_preimage_of_nonempty (s : Set N)
    (f : G →* N) (hs : (f ⁻¹' s).Nonempty) : f.ker ≤ closure (f ⁻¹' s) := by
  obtain ⟨g, hg⟩ := hs
  refine' le_trans (fun k h ↦ _) (closure_mono (Set.preimage_mono (Set.singleton_subset_iff.2 hg)))
  rw [← mul_inv_cancel_right k g]
  refine' mul_mem (subset_closure _) (inv_mem (subset_closure _)) <;> simp [map_mul, f.mem_ker.1 h]

theorem Subgroup.comap_normalClosure_of_nonempty (s : Set N) (hs : s.Nonempty)
    (f : G →* N) (hf : Surjective f) :
    normalClosure (f ⁻¹' s) = (normalClosure s).comap f := by
  refine' map_injective_of_ker_le f
    ((ker_le_closure_preimage_of_nonempty s f (hs.preimage hf)).trans closure_le_normalClosure)
    (ker_le_comap f (normalClosure s)) _
  rw [map_normalClosure (f ⁻¹' s) f hf, map_comap_eq_self_of_surjective hf,
    Set.image_preimage_eq s hf]
```

@tb65536 I had looked for a proof to weaken the equivalence assumption so I am glad to see this!  

To further the sake of symmetry among the lemmas it may be possible to remove the `NonEmpty` from the assumptions and then do a proof `by_cases H : s.NonEmpty` *if* when `s` is empty you can derive a contradiction.  It is getting in the wee hours of the morning here so I may be totally off with this.  Feel free to add this if you think this is a decent idea (if not, I would like to hear back on the reasons so I can learn why) and go ahead and push a commit.
@eric-wieser what should be done here?  I want to get this PR across the line as I have a couple of branches blocked on it.
Given this is not a strict generalization, these should be in addition to the existing lemmas not instead of them. I don't care whether they are in this PR or a follow-up.
I say we just keep them in a separate PR then.
